<h2>John Leighton, F.S.A. (1822-1912)</h2>
<img src="../../../icons2/vntop.gif"/>
<p class="bc">
[<a href ="../../../index.html">Victorian Web Home</a> —> 
<a href="../../index.html">Visual Arts</a> —> 
<a href= "../index.html">Illustration</a>]</p>
</div>

<div id="main">
<br/>
<br/>

<a href = "../../design/books/king/13.html"><img src="../../design/books/king/13.jpg" alt="1title1" height="144" border="0" class = "floatright"/></a>

<p class="tc">John Leighton: the frontispiece of his <span class="tcartwork">Tubular Transit for London (1902); British Library no. 8235.bb.87(4).</span></p>

<p class="one">John Leighton, &ldquo;a long-lived man of exceptional ability with wide-ranging interests&rdquo; (<a href = "../../design/books/king/leighton.html">King</a>) was not only a prolific book illustrator but he also designed the covers of books for more than 60 publishers and &ldquo;wrote and illustrated a number of works in the 1840s under the pseudonym of Luke Limner, almost certainly taking his pseudonym from St Luke, the patron saint of artists&rdquo; (King). 
</p>

<h3>Related Material</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="../../design/books/king/leighton.html">The Book Cover Designs of John Leighton, F.S.A.</a></li>

</ul>

